// Water Freezing Simulation
//
// Models a realistic freezing scenario: randomized stone terrain at the bottom,
// two layers of liquid water on top, and open air above. The ambient temperature
// ramps from 5°C (278.15 K) down to −20°C (253.15 K) over 24 simulated hours,
// then holds. The simulation runs until all water has frozen into ice.
//
// Expected behaviour (matches real-world lake physics):
//   - Top water layer (exposed to air) freezes first (~day 8–9)
//   - Bottom water layer (insulated by ice + stone) takes much longer (~100+ days)
//   - The ice cap insulates the water below, slowing the freezing front
//
// The convective boundary condition (boundary_htc) models the fact that real
// air–water heat transfer is convection-dominated (h ≈ 10–50 W/(m²·K)), which
// pure conduction through 1 m voxels cannot capture. With boundary_htc set,
// boundary air voxels are clamped to ambient temperature each tick.
//
// NOTE: When native octree physics with LOD-based dynamic resolution is
// implemented, sub-voxel resolution at phase interfaces will capture the
// freezing front more accurately and may reduce reliance on the boundary HTC
// correction. The scenario parameters should be revisited at that time.

SimulationScenario(
    name: "Water Freezing",
    description: "Two water layers over stone terrain cool from 5°C to −20°C; all water should freeze into ice",

    grid_size: 12,

    // Initial temperature: 5°C (278.15 K)
    ambient_temperature: 278.15,
    ambient_pressure: 101325.0,

    // Ramp to −20°C (253.15 K) over 24 hours (86400 s), then hold
    ambient_schedule: RampThenHold(
        end_temperature: 253.15,
        ramp_seconds: 86400.0,
    ),

    // Convective boundary: clamp boundary air to ambient each tick
    boundary_htc: Some(25.0),

    material_source: FromAssets,
    reaction_source: FromAssets,

    regions: [
        // Layer 1: randomized stone terrain filling y=0 through y=0..3
        RandomHeightmap(
            material: "Stone",
            x_range: (0, 11),
            z_range: (0, 11),
            y_min: 0,
            y_max: 3,
            seed: 42,
        ),
        // Layer 2: water fills y=4 and y=5 (two 1-m layers)
        Fill(
            material: "Water",
            min: (0, 4, 0),
            max: (11, 5, 11),
        ),
        // Air fills the rest (y=6..11) by default (grid starts as air)
    ],

    // dt = 600 s (10 minutes per tick).
    // ticks = 25000 max ≈ 174 simulated days — enough for both layers to freeze.
    dt: 600.0,
    ticks: 25000,

    // Run until all assertions pass (convergence-based stopping)
    stop_condition: UntilAllPass,

    assertions: [
        // All water must have frozen
        MaterialAbsent(material: "Water"),
        // There must be ice present
        MaterialCountGt(material: "Ice", min_count: 1),
        // No chemical reactions should fire (pure thermal scenario)
        NoReactions,
    ],
)
